{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-03536/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-03536"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:35:36"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["plan américain"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["eye-level"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["group shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["The man speaks, and one woman leaves."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-03536","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-03536"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/f29d04e0-0eb9-4a89-9a31-8e398630787f","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T15:59:10.084Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>It’s not enough for Reynolds to be in a relationship with Alma and to be dressing her. He also wishes her to align her tastes with his (another instance of the “hunger” theme).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1323.0686406460295,416.6083445491252,467.7254374158815,381.15746971736206"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/c07db605-0397-4493-81cc-8ef968b44074","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T15:59:26.234Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Cyril and Reynolds both react against Alma’s dislike of the fabric. While Cyril argues its worth because it is loved by their client, Reynolds simply says, “It is right because it is right, because it is beautiful.” He presents his opinion as logical and objectively true rather than subjective, dismissing Alma’s opinion of the clothes he dresses her in. He treats her as a canvas for his art, a blank slate whose opinions he can overwrite based on his taste. Alma refuses to give up her own opinion, however. When Cyril says that Alma’s taste may change, she simply replies that it may not. She refuses to submit to them.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:277.792732166891,114.26648721399737,264.8721399730821,301.04979811574697"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1/3cd71cce-2cdf-476d-aeea-665bef29bd62","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T15:59:47.602Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>This exchange draws from Mary Blume’s biography of Spanish designer Cristóbal Balenciaga. Writing about his lead saleswoman, Florette Chelot, she reports: “Sometimes he called her into the studio. ‘It was never for a question of taste but to ask if a certain client liked this. He knew he could trust me. He would say, Florette’s right, she’s always right’” (Blume, <em>The Master of Us All</em>, 100).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-03536/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1034.9394347240916,97.46971736204586,306.2180349932705,162.79946164199185"}}}]}]}]}